Overview

This script looks into Stackoverflowâ€™s R-Questions tags and explores relations. Questions are tagged with at least one tag, but the majority have more than one. For these questions, I will look into the occurance of pairs (e.g.Â ggplot2-histogram, or shiny-javascript,..etc.) and see the most frequent pairs.

At the end, we will be able to make statements such as:

  • â€œshinyâ€ appeared in x questions with â€œggplot2â€

  • â€œlegendâ€ is the 2nd most frequently mentioned tags with â€œggplot2â€

  • â€¦etc.

This could help identify the most frequently mentioned pairs of tags.

Data Analysis

Loading Libraries and Reading Data

# load libraries
library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(tidyr)
library(DT)

#read tags data
dat <- read.csv("../rquestions/Tags.csv",stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Exploring Dataset

# count the frequency of each tag
datx <- dat %>%
        group_by(Tag) %>%
        summarise(N=n()) %>%
        arrange(desc(N))

We can see the frequency of each tag as follows:

Tags Pairs

Here we will select the questions with more than one tag (in addition to R) and do the following:

  • Step1: get all the tags corresponding to question ID
  • Step2: find all pair combinations from these tags
  • Step3: combine all the pairs in one dataframe

Step1 : get all the tags corresponding to question ID

# group by question ID and nest (for questions with more than one tag (+R))
datn <- dat %>% 
        group_by(Id) %>% 
        filter(n()>1) %>% 
        nest(.key="Tags")

Now if we lookk at a certain question ID, we find all the tags in one list:

  # A tibble: 1 x 2
       Id             Tags
    <int>           <list>
  1 79709 <tibble [4 x 1]>

and we can get them :

datn$Tags[1]
  [[1]]
  # A tibble: 4 x 1
                 Tag
               <chr>
  1           memory
  2         function
  3 global-variables
  4     side-effects

Step2: find all pair combinations from these tags

Now, we will get all the possible pairs from the questionsâ€™ tags:

#function to get all the combinations from a list
GetPairs <- function(x) {
        combn(x[[1]],2) %>% 
                t %>% 
                as.data.frame(row.names=NULL,stringsAsFactors=FALSE) 
}

datn <- datn %>% 
        mutate(pairs=map(Tags,GetPairs))

For the same row we checked in the previous step, we can see that the pairs are as follows:

datn$pairs[1]
  [[1]]
                  V1               V2
  1           memory         function
  2           memory global-variables
  3           memory     side-effects
  4         function global-variables
  5         function     side-effects
  6 global-variables     side-effects

Step3: combine all the pairs in one dataframe

Now we will combine all the pairs for all questions, in one dataframe

dat_pairs <- plyr::rbind.fill(datn$pairs)

# put pairs in the same order
dat_pairs <- dat_pairs %>% 
        mutate(firstV=map2_chr(V1,V2,function(x,y) sort(c(x,y))[1]),
               secondV=map2_chr(V1,V2,function(x,y) sort(c(x,y))[2])
        ) %>% 
        select(-V1,-V2)

# count the frequency of each pair
pair_freq <- dat_pairs %>% 
        group_by(firstV,secondV) %>% 
        summarise(pair_count=n()) %>% 
        arrange(desc(pair_count))

Now we have the frequency of each pair as follows:

datatable(pair_freq)

Tag-Pairs for a Certain Tag

Here we can pick one tag and see all the other tags that appear with it and the frequency of each.

# Get all pairs with a certain tag
GetTagPairs <- function(tag) {
     
        tagx <- pair_freq %>% 
                filter(firstV==tag|secondV==tag) %>% 
                arrange(desc(pair_count))   
        
        tagx[tagx$secondV == tag, 
             c("firstV", "secondV")] <- tagx[tagx$secondV == tag, 
                                             c("secondV", "firstV")] 
        
        return(tagx)
}

Example: ggplot2 Pairs

ex <- GetTagPairs("ggplot2")

datatable(ex)
